> Gobble gobble: it's time for Thanksgiving! There's no way we weren't going to pull out all the stops for a holiday that's all about food (and giving thanks… but mostly food). So we're offering up a special stuffing that will be welcome on any feasting table. It's got cranberries, sage, toasty bread, and our special harvest spice blend. All you need to make it complete is a few of your other favorite Thanksgiving dishes (and six to eight hungry mouths to feed it to).

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Cut @demi-baguettes{3} and @white bread{3%slices} into ½-inch pieces, keeping them separate. Place baguette pieces on one #baking sheet{}. Place white bread pieces on another sheet. Toast both in oven until crisp, and golden, ~{8-10%minutes} for the white bread and ~{12-15%minutes} for the baguette.

Lightly grease a #baking dish{} with @butter{1%tbsp} (we used 1 TBSP butter in an 8 x 11-inch baking dish). Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}. Mince @garlic{2%cloves}. Finely dice @celery{2%stalks}. Pick @sage{¼%ounce} leaves from stems and finely chop; discard stems. Core @apple{1}, then cut into ½-inch cubes.

Melt @butter{8%tbsp} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add onion, garlic, and celery. Cook, tossing, until translucent and very soft, ~{5-7%minutes}. Stir in @fall spice blend{1%tablespoon} and sage. Cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Stir @Ocean Spray® Craisins® Dried Cranberries{2.32%ounce}, apple, and toasted breads into pot. Pour @water{} into pot, ¼ cup a time, until bread is moist but not soggy— you may need up to 2 cups. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{4}. Poke bread with a #wooden spoon{} to break it up. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Beat @eggs{1} with a fork in a #small bowl{}, then stir into pot (use the other @eggs{1} as you like).

Transfer contents of pot to greased baking dish. Bake in oven until golden and crisp on top and tender on bottom, about ~{30%minutes}.

Let stuffing cool a few minutes after baking, then serve next to your favorite Thanksgiving dishes.